 <H1>A Note on Range Variables</H1> 
 <P><UL>
<LI><H2>Really needed only if the same relation appears twice in the FROM clause.  The previous query can also be written as:</H2>
</UL></P>
<P><UL>
SELECT  S.sname
<BR></UL><UL>
FROM     Sailors S, Reserves R
</UL><UL>
WHERE  S.sid=R.sid AND bid=103</UL></P>
<P><UL>
SELECT  sname
<BR></UL><UL>
FROM     Sailors, Reserves 
</UL><UL>
WHERE  Sailors.sid=Reserves.sid
</UL><UL>
               AND bid=103</UL></P>
<P><UL>
It is good style,
<BR></UL><UL>
however, to use
</UL><UL>
range variables
</UL><UL>
always!</UL></P>
<P><UL>
OR<BR></UL></P>
<P></P> 
<P>
<TABLE>
  <TD HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=100> <A HREF="tsld005.htm">Diapositiva precedente</A> </TD>
  <TD HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=100> <A HREF="tsld007.htm">Diapositiva successiva</A> </TD>
  <TD HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=150> <A HREF="tsld001.htm">Torna alla prima diaposiva</A> </TD>
  <TD HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=150> <A HREF="sld006.htm">Visualizza versione grafica</A> </TD>
</TABLE>
<BR>
</P>



